Notfallpraxen in Baden-WÃ¼rttemberg

Marcel Reinmuth

2025-01-18

1 Introduction

Notfallpraxen are emergency healthcare facilities in Germany that provide medical services during hours when regular doctorsâ offices are closed, such as weekends, evenings, and holidays. These facilities are critical for providing accessible care without requiring patients to visit a hospital. However, in 2025, there are plans to close several of these facilities in Baden-WÃ¼rttemberg (BW), which may impact accessibility for residents.

2 Data Overview

The dataset includes information on Notfallpraxen locations, their service areas (isochrones), and the population impacted within travel times of 30, 40, and 50 minutes.

# Load data
load("kvbw_er/kvbw_data.RData")

# Data summaries
n_total <- nrow(doctors)
n_closed <- nrow(doctors |> filter(class == "werden geschlossen"))
n_kept <- n_total - n_closed

  • Total Notfallpraxen in BW: 95

  • Number planned to close in 2025: 18

  • Number to remain open: 77

tmap_mode("view")
## tmap mode set to interactive viewing
tm_shape(dissolved_isochrones_all) +
  tm_fill(
    col = "AA_MINS",
    style = "cat", # Ensure categories for isochrones
    palette = c("30" = "#FFFACD", "40" = "#FFA07A", "50" = "#8B0000"), # Subtle yellow, orange, and vine red
    title = "Travel Time"
  ) +
  tm_shape(doctors) +
  tm_dots(
    col = "class",
    palette = c("bleiben" = "#228B22", "werden geschlossen" = "#B22222"), # Subtle green and dark red
    size = 0.1,
    title = "Doctor Status"
  ) +
  tm_layout(title = "All Isochrones")
